President Obama spoke with Prime Minister Abe of Japan regarding the situation in Ukraine. They both agreed that Russia's actions pose a threat to international peace and security, and emphasized the importance of preserving Ukraine's sovereignty and territorial integrity. They pledged to work with other G-7 partners to hold Russia accountable for its obligations and commitments to Ukraine, but acknowledged that there is a diplomatic opportunity for Russia to resolve the situation in a way that benefits all parties involved. Additionally, they agreed to support Ukraine's government in stabilizing its economy and preparing for upcoming elections, both bilaterally and through the International Monetary Fund. The President also mentioned that his upcoming visit to Japan in April will provide an important opportunity to advance various diplomatic, defense, and trade initiatives between the United States and Japan in Asia and globally.